      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Safer, Slower Park</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John P Tanton letter, responding to May 29 front-page article, welcomes efforts to reduce noise pollution in Central Park (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Efforts to reduce noise pollution in Central Park (front page, May 29) are to be welcomed. There is a comparable need to enhance the safety of park users.</p>
        <p>Having enjoyed strolling there three or four times a week for nearly 30 years, I appreciate the absence of motor traffic (except on the transverses) on weekends.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Efforts to reduce noise pollution in Central Park (front page, May 29) are to be welcomed. There is a comparable need to enhance the safety of park users.</p>
        <p>Having enjoyed strolling there three or four times a week for nearly 30 years, I appreciate the absence of motor traffic (except on the transverses) on weekends.</p>
        <p>Would the authorities consider setting aside just one day a month -- perhaps the first Sunday -- when cycling and in-line skating would also be prohibited?</p>
        <p>This would enable many elderly and infirm people, currently fearful of being knocked over by these speed enthusiasts, to renew their acquaintance with this priceless city resource, and enjoy its amenities.</p>
        <p>JOHN P. TANTON  New York, May 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
